In my previous post, I stated that some library (SPECFUN by W.D. Cody) computes \(e^{-\frac{x^2}{2}}\) the following way: xsq = fint(x * 1.6) / 1.6; del = (x - xsq) * (x + xsq); result = exp(-xsq * xsq * 0.5) * exp(-del *0.5);
where fint(z) computes the floor of z.
Why 1.6? An integer divided by 1.6 will be an exact representation of the corresponding number in double: 1.6 because of 16 (dividing by 1.

Some library computes the Gaussian density function $$e^{-\frac{x^2}{2}}$$ the following way: xsq = fint(x * 1.6) / 1.6; del = (x - xsq) * (x + xsq); result = exp(-xsq * xsq * 0.5) * exp(-del *0.5);
where fint(z) computes the floor of z.
Basically, x*x is rewritten as xsq*xsq+del. I have seen that trick once before, but I just can&rsquo;t figure out where and why (except that it is probably related to high accuracy issues).
